Trust Is Risk Game

Trust Is Risk Game explained












   j = 0
   while (TRUE)
      j += 1
      v = chooseFrom(V)
      Turn = strategies[v](G[0], v, H)
      (G[j], Cap[v, j], H[j]) =
         executeTurn(G[j-1], v, Cap[v, j-1], Turn)
  • chooseFrom() chooses a player for this turn.
  • strategies[v]() returns a Turn chosen by player v. This player has full knowledge of the game history.
  • executeTurn() checks the validity of Turn. Subsequently, it creates the new graph G[j] and updates the history and player's v capital accordingly.

(Indirect) Trust definition

How much does Alice trust Bob?

We define indirect trust as the maximum loss Alice can suffer if Bob steals all incoming direct trust and the rest of the players attempt to replenish their stolen funds.

Let's define the relevant strategies.

Strategies

  • Idle Strategy: Pass your turn

  • Evil Strategy: Confiscate all incoming and outgoing direct trust, turning it into (exclusively spendable) capital (Steal all your incoming direct trust and exit the game)

  • Conservative Strategy: Replenish previously stolen outgoing direct trust by stealing incoming direct trust (Steal as much as was stolen from you since last time you played)

When there exists one Idle and one Evil player and the rest are Conservative, we have the Transitive Game (variation of Trust Is Risk Game)

Trust flow theorem

IndirectTrust_{A \rightarrow B} = maxFlow(A, B)
IndirectTrustAB=maxFlow(A,B)IndirectTrust_{A \rightarrow B} = maxFlow(A, B)IndirectTrustAB=maxFlow(A,B)

Proof Sketch:

  • Every maximum flow corresponds to a Transitive Game with actions instead of flows

  • Every Transitive Game is made up solely of actions that also constitute a valid flow

Sybil Attack

Collusion = Corrupted Set Sybil Set

Corrupted Set: Originally trustworthy players, now compromised by Eve. May be directly trusted by Alice.

Sybil Set: Players fabricated by Eve. May be directly trusted only by players inside the Collusion.

Collusion

Sybil Resilience

Trust_{Alice \rightarrow (Corrupted \cup Sybil)} = Trust_{Alice \rightarrow Corrupted}
TrustAlice(CorruptedSybil)=TrustAliceCorruptedTrust_{Alice \rightarrow (Corrupted \cup Sybil)} = Trust_{Alice \rightarrow Corrupted}TrustAlice(CorruptedSybil)=TrustAliceCorrupted

Proof Sketch:

The Sybil set has no incoming direct trust from players outside the Collusion. Thus incoming direct trust to the Collusion cannot exceed the incoming direct trust to the Corrupted set alone.
